1. What is Swagger/OpenAPI?

Swagger (now called OpenAPI) is a standard for describing REST APIs.
It allows you to generate interactive documentation for your API, so developers can see
endpoints, try them out, and understand request/response formats.

In Spring Boot, the most popular tool for this is SpringDoc OpenAPI.

2. Why Use Swagger/OpenAPI?

(i) Automatic documentation: No need to write docs by hand.
(ii) Interactive UI: Lets you test endpoints directly from the browser.
(iii) Clear contracts: Shows request/response formats, parameters, and status codes.
(iv) Helps frontend, QA, and other backend teams understand and use your API.

3. Setting Up Swagger/OpenAPI in Spring Boot

a.Add Dependency
For Maven, add to your pom.xml:

<dependency>
    <groupId>org.springdoc</groupId>
    <artifactId>springdoc-openapi-starter-webmvc-ui</artifactId>
    <version>2.3.0</version>
</dependency>

b.Run Your App

Start your Spring Boot application.

Visit:
http://localhost:8080/swagger-ui.html
or http://localhost:8080/swagger-ui/index.html

You’ll see an interactive UI with all your REST endpoints!

4. Documenting Your API with Annotations

SpringDoc/OpenAPI uses annotations to add details to your API documentation.

(i) @Operation
Describes what an endpoint does.

Ex:

import io.swagger.v3.oas.annotations.Operation;

@Operation(summary = "Get user by ID", description = "Returns a single user")
@GetMapping("/users/{id}")
public ResponseEntity<User> getUserById(@PathVariable Long id) { ... }

(ii) @ApiResponses and @ApiResponse

Describe possible responses (status codes, messages).

Ex:

import io.swagger.v3.oas.annotations.responses.ApiResponses;
import io.swagger.v3.oas.annotations.responses.ApiResponse;

@ApiResponses(value = {
    @ApiResponse(responseCode = "200", description = "User found"),
    @ApiResponse(responseCode = "404", description = "User not found")
})
@GetMapping("/users/{id}")
public ResponseEntity<User> getUserById(@PathVariable Long id) { ... }

(iii) @Parameter

Describes a method parameter.

Ex:

import io.swagger.v3.oas.annotations.Parameter;

@GetMapping("/users/{id}")
public ResponseEntity<User> getUserById(
    @Parameter(description = "ID of the user to be retrieved") @PathVariable Long id) { ... }


5. Example: Full Controller with Documentation

Ex:

@RestController
@RequestMapping("/users")
public class UserController {

    @Operation(summary = "Get all users", description = "Returns a list of all users")
    @GetMapping
    public List<User> getAllUsers() {
        return userRepository.findAll();
    }

    @Operation(summary = "Get user by ID", description = "Returns a single user")
    @ApiResponses(value = {
        @ApiResponse(responseCode = "200", description = "User found"),
        @ApiResponse(responseCode = "404", description = "User not found")
    })
    @GetMapping("/{id}")
    public ResponseEntity<User> getUserById(
        @Parameter(description = "ID of the user to be retrieved") @PathVariable Long id) {
        return userRepository.findById(id)
            .map(ResponseEntity::ok)
            .orElse(ResponseEntity.notFound().build());
    }
}


6. What Does the Swagger UI Show?

a.All your endpoints, grouped by controller.
b.For each endpoint: HTTP method, URL, description, parameters, request/response examples, and
c.possible status codes.
d.A “Try it out” button to test endpoints directly from the browser.
